{
  "texts": [
    "We note that, besides the proof of theorem 3.1, this choice has no effect, so that theorems of section 4 still hold for the full system where (1 -α) 2 SI, S * I * in the stochastic terms are replaced with (1 -α)SI (M), S * I (M), with the caveat that one must assume global existence of a solution which is eventually nonnegative.",
    "This is because in the proof of theorems 4.2 and 4.4, the only bound that we use for the stochastic terms is the total population bound b δ which works just as well for the full stochastic terms as for the reduced ones.",
    "Further, with or without this modification, system (3.1) captures the same behavior in the asymptotic regimes studied in section 4 since those regimes alternately involve the whole population becoming compliant so that (1 -α)SI (M) → (1 -α) 2 SI, the whole population becoming noncompliant so that S * I (M) → S * I *, and similar observations can be made regarding the stochastic terms involving spread of noncompliance.We note that adding together all equations from (3.1) shows that the total population N total = S + I + R + S * + I * + R * is deterministic and satisfies the same bound derived above from (2.3) and (2.4).",
    "For our purposes, we will be considering positive, deterministic initial data (S 0, I 0, R 0, S * 0, I * 0, R * 0).",
    "The assumption that initial data is deterministic is necessary for some of stability results below."
  ]
}